<h2>Understanding What is EM &amp; How it Works?</h2>
<p><a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/font-size#em=
s" target=3D"_blank">EM</a> is a CSS unit that is relative to the font-size=
 of the parent element.</p>
<p>Let's understand it with an example.</p>
<p>Let's say there's a <span class=3D"has-text-weight-bold">&lt;div&gt;</sp=
an> and you have defined the font-size for it to be <span class=3D"has-text=
-weight-semibold">16px</span>. Now if you use a <span class=3D"has-text-wei=
ght-bold">&lt;p&gt;</span> tag and give it the size of <span class=3D"has-t=
ext-weight-semibold">1em</span>, then the font-size of <span class=3D"has-t=
ext-weight-bold">&lt;p&gt;</span> would be equivalent to <span class=3D"has=
-text-weight-semibold">16px</span> because em is relative css unit to the f=
ont-size of the parent element.</p>
<p>Similarly, if the font-size of the <span class=3D"has-text-weight-bold">=
&lt;div&gt;</span> would be <span class=3D"has-text-weight-semibold">20px</=
span>, then the font-size of <span class=3D"has-text-weight-bold">&lt;p&gt;=
</span> would be <span class=3D"has-text-weight-bold">20px</span>.</p>
<h2>How do you convert PX to EM?</h2>
<p>Converting px to em is an easy math. You just have to divide the px valu=
e that you want to convert with the base font size a.k.a parent element's f=
ont size.</p>
<p>The formula to convert pixels to em:</p>
<p class=3D"has-text-weight-bold has-background-light has-text-centered p-5=
" data-slot-rendered-content=3D"true">em <span class=3D"has-text-weight-nor=
mal">=3D</span> px <span class=3D"has-text-weight-normal">/</span> base fon=
t-size</p>
